There are a number of stories about the origin of foot binding before its establishment during the Song dynasty. One of these involves the story of a favourite consort of theÂ Southern QiÂ emperorÂ Xiao Baojuan,Â Pan YunuÂ (died 501 AD), who had delicate feet and danced barefoot on a floor decorated with golden lotus flower design. The emperor expressed admiration and said that "lotus springs from her every step!", a reference to the Buddhist legend of Padmavati under whose feet lotus springs forth.

Unfortunately, there is no evidence that Consort Pan ever bound her feet. The general view is that the practice is likely to have originated in the time of the 10th-centuryÂ Emperor Li YuÂ of theÂ Southern Tang, just before theÂ Song dynasty.Â Li Yu created a six-foot tall golden lotus decorated with precious stones and pearls, and asked his concubine Yao Niang (çª…å¨˜) to bind her feet in white silk into the shape of the crescent moon, and perform a ballet-like dance on the points of her feet on the lotus. Yao Niang's dance was said to be so graceful that others sought to imitate her.

